actually have in common.

57
00:03:03,349 --> 00:03:06,386
If you look at the photos
at the bottom of the slide,

58
00:03:06,386 --> 00:03:10,190
these are all photos of tissues
from patients that are diagnosed

59
00:03:10,190 --> 00:03:11,324
with these diseases.

60
00:03:11,324 --> 00:03:13,326
And you'll notice
these dark spots

61
00:03:13,326 --> 00:03:16,062
that are on the
slide in these cells.

62
00:03:16,062 --> 00:03:19,098
Those are proteins
that are aggregated,

63
00:03:19,098 --> 00:03:21,801
a common feature of
all five diseases.

64
00:03:21,801 --> 00:03:24,137
What that means at
the molecular level

65
00:03:24,137 --> 00:03:26,039
is that proteins
that are normally

66
00:03:26,039 --> 00:03:29,909
pretty flexible in a cell
to do their normal function,

67
00:03:29,909 --> 00:03:31,311
they are somehow--

68
00:03:31,311 --> 00:03:33,213
they somehow get
clumped together

69
00:03:33,213 --> 00:03:36,049
in what we call these
protein aggregates.

70
00:03:36,049 --> 00:03:39,319
We don't always know how they
happen or why they happen,

71
00:03:39,319 --> 00:03:42,622
but I like to think of some
cellular protein highway

72
00:03:42,622 --> 00:03:46,125
where one path gets cut off,
leading to this cellular protein

73
00:03:46,125 --> 00:03:46,960
traffic jam.

74
00:03:46,960 --> 00:03:50,196
Similar to if you were to say
shut down the Sumner Tunnel.

75
00:03:50,196 --> 00:03:51,798
And now there's
a giant aggregate

76
00:03:51,798 --> 00:03:53,700
of cars on the way
to the airport.

77
00:03:53,700 --> 00:03:56,436
With that in mind, it's
important to consider

78
00:03:56,436 --> 00:03:59,439
ways to prevent these
cellular protein traffic

79
00:03:59,439 --> 00:04:01,708
jams from happening
in the first place.

80
00:04:01,708 --> 00:04:05,445
Luckily, there's a protein
that I care about called DNAJB6

81
00:04:05,445 --> 00:04:08,915
that is already very good
at directing protein traffic

82
00:04:08,915 --> 00:04:10,617
and preventing these aggregates.

83
00:04:10,617 --> 00:04:14,287
But as you've seen, it doesn't
always work in these diseases.

84
00:04:14,287 --> 00:04:16,990
Based on what we
know about DNAJB6,

85
00:04:16,990 --> 00:04:19,225
my lab has three
big-picture goals.

86
00:04:19,225 --> 00:04:21,160
We want to develop
new chemical tools

87
00:04:21,160 --> 00:04:23,696
that we can use to detect
these aggregates earlier

88
00:04:23,696 --> 00:04:25,331
than we can right now.

89
00:04:25,331 --> 00:04:27,967
We want to learn more
about the mechanisms

90
00:04:27,967 --> 00:04:31,204
that DNAJB uses to direct
protein traffic to see

91
00:04:31,204 --> 00:04:33,940
if there's any clues there on
what we could do as chemists.

92
00:04:33,940 --> 00:04:37,510
And we want to discover
chemicals, small molecules that

93
00:04:37,510 --> 00:04:41,314
can work with DNAJB6 to either
activate or mimic its activity

94
00:04:41,314 --> 00:04:43,416
and prevent aggregates
from happening.

95
00:04:43,416 --> 00:04:45,918
And I was really lucky to
recruit three fabulous graduate

96
00:04:45,918 --> 00:04:48,888
students in my first year
