00:11:55,981 --> 00:11:59,018
in college-age adolescents,
in women, and low-income

250
00:11:59,018 --> 00:12:00,453
and minority groups.

251
00:12:00,453 --> 00:12:02,254
Looking at these
statistics, it's

252
00:12:02,254 --> 00:12:05,224
hard not to feel that we are
living in a pandemic of stress

253
00:12:05,224 --> 00:12:07,860
with marginalized
communities and our youth,

254
00:12:07,860 --> 00:12:12,064
the very future of our nation,
bearing the heaviest burden.

255
00:12:12,064 --> 00:12:13,999
The consequences
of this on society

256
00:12:13,999 --> 00:12:16,435
are massive, damaging not
just our mental health

257
00:12:16,435 --> 00:12:18,037
but our physical health as well.

258
00:12:18,037 --> 00:12:20,139
Children, for example,
who experience

259
00:12:20,139 --> 00:12:23,409
severe early life stress as
measured by high ACE scores,

260
00:12:23,409 --> 00:12:25,778
lose over a decade
of life expectancy

261
00:12:25,778 --> 00:12:27,480
and are at higher
risk for conditions

262
00:12:27,480 --> 00:12:31,450
like cardiovascular disease,
infertility, and cancer.

263
00:12:31,450 --> 00:12:34,854
This association between stress
and worse health outcomes

264
00:12:34,854 --> 00:12:36,889
is also seen in animal models.

265
00:12:36,889 --> 00:12:40,726
For example, early life stress
reduces survival in wild baboons

266
00:12:40,726 --> 00:12:43,429
and cause mice that are
raised in lab environments

267
00:12:43,429 --> 00:12:45,498
to develop predictable
pathologies,

268
00:12:45,498 --> 00:12:48,200
like making their
very hair turn gray.

269
00:12:48,200 --> 00:12:51,570
These observations tell us
that these associations between

270
00:12:51,570 --> 00:12:55,141
stress and worse health outcomes
cannot be explained entirely

271
00:12:55,141 --> 00:12:58,244
by diet, smoking, and access
to health care services.

272
00:12:58,244 --> 00:13:02,815
And it begs the question of what
biological processes link stress

273
00:13:02,815 --> 00:13:06,118
to increased disease
and mortality risk.

274
00:13:06,118 --> 00:13:08,320
I'm a neuroscientist,
and my lab studies

275
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:11,223
how the brain controls essential
functions like breathing

276
00:13:11,223 --> 00:13:12,191
and heart rate.

277
00:13:12,191 --> 00:13:14,560
And we see stress not
just as a feeling,

278
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:18,664
but as a biological program with
specific purpose and patterns.

279
00:13:18,664 --> 00:13:21,901
When we face a threat, the
brain primes the body for action

280
00:13:21,901 --> 00:13:24,003
by triggering the
sympathetic nervous system

281
00:13:24,003 --> 00:13:26,972
to release norepinephrine,
causing rapid breathing,

282
00:13:26,972 --> 00:13:28,841
a racing heart, and sweating.

283
00:13:28,841 --> 00:13:31,377
These circuits also
signal endocrine centers

284
00:13:31,377 --> 00:13:32,878
like the adrenal
glands to produce

285
00:13:32,878 --> 00:13:36,749
cortisol and other hormones,
keeping the body on high alert.

286
00:13:36,749 --> 00:13:39,051
Cells throughout the body
receive these signals

287
00:13:39,051 --> 00:13:40,953
and are forever changed.

288
00:13:40,953 --> 00:13:43,622
With new tools, we can
now monitor and target

289
00:13:43,622 --> 00:13:46,225
these pathways with
unprecedented precision

290
00:13:46,225 --> 00:13:49,061
to ask which precise
circuits are disrupted

291
00:13:49,061 --> 00:13:51,163
by chronic and severe stress.

292
00:13:51,163 --> 00:13:53,399
How do stress signals
affect different cell types

293
00:13:53,399 --> 00:13:56,101
throughout the body, and how
are these changes remembered

294
00:13:56,101 --> 00:13:57,703
at the molecular scale?

295
00:13:57,703 --> 00:13:59,371
Through this lens,
we can view stress

296
00:13:59,371 --> 00:14:03,275
as a predictable program that
can be tracked and treated.

297
00:14:03,275 --> 00:14:06,745
To understand this, we're
collaborating with other Boston

298
00:14:06,745 --> 00:14:10,850
area labs, using animal models
to control stress exposures,

299
00:14:10,850 --> 00:14:13,619
and then using advanced
imaging and molecular tools

300
00:14:13,619 --> 00:14:15,487
to track within
individual animals

301
00:14:15,487 --> 00:14:17,990
how this rewires brain
activity and disrupts

302
00:14:17,990 --> 00:14:19,692
physiological systems.

303
00:14:19,692 --> 00:14:23,028
These comprehensive data sets
capture a more holistic view

304
00:14:23,028 --> 00:14:25,731
of stress and are helping
us predict causal brain

305
00:14:25,731 --> 00:14:28,267
changes that alter
bodily states and lead

306
00:14:28,267 --> 00:14:30,369
to stress-related disease.

307
00:14:30,369 --> 00:14:32,838
Looking ahead, addressing
this health crisis

308
00:14:32,838 --> 00:14:35,407
requires new perspectives
and solutions.

309
00:14:35,407 --> 00:14:38,911
As for cancer research, we
must both learn core principles

310
00:14:38,911 --> 00:14:41,380
while also embracing
stress' complexity,

311
00:14:41,380 --> 00:14:45,050
and endotypes if we want to
advance precision treatments.

312
00:14:45,050 --> 00:14:47,686
This effort will rest on
pillars of collaboration

313
00:14:47,686 --> 00:14:50,890
across disciplines to better
understand the molecular scars

314
00:14:50,890 --> 00:14:53,926
of stress and to build
evidence-based diagnostics

315
00:14:53,926 --> 00:14:55,928
and interventions
within our community.

316
00:14:55,928 --> 00:14:59,064
And I for one am looking
forward to this bright future.

317
00:14:59,064 --> 00:15:00,466
Thank you all for
your attention.

318
00:15:00,466 --> 00:15:03,869
