319
00:15:03,869 --> 00:15:20,653

320
00:15:20,653 --> 00:15:21,854
Good morning.

321
00:15:21,854 --> 00:15:23,188
My name is Sinisa Hrvatin.

322
00:15:23,188 --> 00:15:24,490
I'm honored to be here.

323
00:15:24,490 --> 00:15:26,525
I want you this
morning to imagine

324
00:15:26,525 --> 00:15:29,695
a world in which suspended
animation were possible.

325
00:15:29,695 --> 00:15:33,899
A world in which a 10-year-old
girl suffering an incurable

326
00:15:33,899 --> 00:15:36,335
disease, like
maybe glioblastoma,

327
00:15:36,335 --> 00:15:40,372
instead of imminently dying,
has the choice to enter a state

328
00:15:40,372 --> 00:15:43,609
of suspended animation for
a few years, maybe a decade,

329
00:15:43,609 --> 00:15:46,378
and then wake up at a time
in which there is a treatment

330
00:15:46,378 --> 00:15:49,348
or perhaps even a
cure to that disease.

331
00:15:49,348 --> 00:15:54,053
I know this is currently
science fiction, pretty much

332
00:15:54,053 --> 00:15:55,955
complete science
fiction, but what

333
00:15:55,955 --> 00:15:58,590
I want to share with you today
is that there are animals

334
00:15:58,590 --> 00:16:01,860
in nature that have the
ability to enter similar states

335
00:16:01,860 --> 00:16:06,098
and that have the ability
to enter something

336
00:16:06,098 --> 00:16:09,568
like suspended animation that I
think we can learn so much from.

337
00:16:09,568 --> 00:16:11,470
And then learn how
to eventually develop

338
00:16:11,470 --> 00:16:13,639
suspended animation for humans.

339
00:16:13,639 --> 00:16:16,642
So I'll share with you examples
of a few of these animals.

340
00:16:16,642 --> 00:16:18,510
This is the Arctic
ground squirrel.

341
00:16:18,510 --> 00:16:21,013
This animal lives
above the Arctic Circle

342
00:16:21,013 --> 00:16:24,450
at very low temperatures,
and during most of the year

343
00:16:24,450 --> 00:16:25,851
it has a normal
body temperature,

344
00:16:25,851 --> 00:16:28,587
just like you and me,
around 37 degrees Celsius.

345
00:16:28,587 --> 00:16:32,491
But during the winter, it can
survive by entering hibernation,

346
00:16:32,491 --> 00:16:35,227
and it can lower its body
temperature all the way down

347
00:16:35,227 --> 00:16:39,932
to around 0 degrees Celsius,
entering a sleep-like state

348
00:16:39,932 --> 00:16:42,001
that we call torpor.

349
00:16:42,001 --> 00:16:45,637
My laboratory studies
how animals enter torpor

350
00:16:45,637 --> 00:16:48,340
and also how do
their cells survive

351
00:16:48,340 --> 00:16:50,309
at these very low temperatures.

352
00:16:50,309 --> 00:16:52,277
And I want to share with
you a couple of things

353
00:16:52,277 --> 00:16:54,279
that we've recently found.

354
00:16:54,279 --> 00:16:57,349
We identified a
population of neurons

355
00:16:57,349 --> 00:17:00,686
in the brain that
controls torpor.

356
00:17:00,686 --> 00:17:05,357
And remarkably, we can actually
initiate a torpor-like state

357
00:17:05,357 --> 00:17:07,826
even in animals that
don't naturally hibernate,

358
00:17:07,826 --> 00:17:09,995
just by stimulating
these neurons.

359
00:17:09,995 --> 00:17:13,298
So here you can see an
example of a laboratory mouse.

360
00:17:13,298 --> 00:17:15,034
This is a thermal camera image.

361
00:17:15,034 --> 00:17:17,870
It has a body temperature
around 37 degrees Celsius.

362
00:17:17,870 --> 00:17:20,105
But when you stimulate
these neurons,

363
00:17:20,105 --> 00:17:21,940
you can lower the
body temperature

364
00:17:21,940 --> 00:17:25,611
of this animal all the way down
to around 25 degrees Celsius.

365
00:17:25,611 --> 00:17:28,280
Now, this is not as low
as a natural hibernator,

366
00:17:28,280 --> 00:17:30,916
but it's actually
really cold for a mouse.

367
00:17:30,916 --> 00:17:34,019
And we can do this not
only for minutes or hours,

368
00:17:34,019 --> 00:17:37,289
but actually for days to weeks,
showing for the first time

369
00:17:37,289 --> 00:17:41,660
that we can induce a
long-term torpor-like state

370
00:17:41,660 --> 00:17:44,863
in an animal that doesn't
naturally hibernate.

371
00:17:44,863 --> 00:17:47,032
We've also, in a
parallel study, started

372
00:17:47,032 --> 00:17:50,002
looking at how do
hibernator cells survive

373
00:17:50,002 --> 00:17:52,438
at these low
temperatures and seeing

374
00:17:52,438 --> 00:17:56,508
whether we can learn from their
mechanisms to improve human cell

375
00:17:56,508 --> 00:17:58,110
cold survival.

376
00:17:58,110 --> 00:18:01,880
And here you can see an example
of a handful of human cell lines

377
00:18:01,880 --> 00:18:04,750
that don't fare very well
at 4 degrees Celsius.

378
00:18:04,750 --> 00:18:08,153
But then when we take
small molecules that

379
00:18:08,153 --> 00:18:11,090
mimic some of the adaptations
that hibernators have

380
00:18:11,090 --> 00:18:14,059
during hibernation and
treat those cells with them,

381
00:18:14,059 --> 00:18:17,129
we can dramatically improve
their cold tolerance.

382
00:18:17,129 --> 00:18:18,831
And you can
immediately imagine how

383
00:18:18,831 --> 00:18:23,335
this could be useful for organ
storage or organ transplantation

384
00:18:23,335 --> 00:18:25,370
and also how
eventually we could use

385
00:18:25,370 --> 00:18:28,874
this to learn how to lower the
temperature of the human body

386
00:18:28,874 --> 00:18:30,976
to lower and lower temperatures.

387
00:18:30,976 --> 00:18:33,412
And finally, perhaps
the greatest example

388
00:18:33,412 --> 00:18:36,482
of suspended animation in nature
are these tardigrades, cute

389
00:18:36,482 --> 00:18:39,251
little organisms that actually
live all over our globe,

390
00:18:39,251 --> 00:18:41,520
from the Arctic
to the Antarctic,

391
00:18:41,520 --> 00:18:43,188
and they have an
incredible ability

392
00:18:43,188 --> 00:18:45,858
to survive being
frozen all the way down

393
00:18:45,858 --> 00:18:48,760
to -150 degrees Celsius.

394
00:18:48,760 --> 00:18:51,563
And they can stay in that
state for months to years

395
00:18:51,563 --> 00:18:55,200
and then come out of it
essentially unharmed.

396
00:18:55,200 --> 00:18:59,071
We're trying to understand
how tardigrades survive this

397
00:18:59,071 --> 00:19:02,107
and whether we can transfer
some of those adaptations

398
00:19:02,107 --> 00:19:03,208
to human cells.

399
00:19:03,208 --> 00:19:07,179
Now life on Earth has evolved
incredible adaptations

400
00:19:07,179 --> 00:19:09,148
to survive in
extreme environments,

401
00:19:09,148 --> 00:19:11,617
and I believe that by
studying these animals,

402
00:19:11,617 --> 00:19:14,386
we'll learn to harness
some of the mechanisms

403
00:19:14,386 --> 00:19:17,222
behind these adaptations
to advance medicine,

404
00:19:17,222 --> 00:19:19,525
perhaps even one day open
the door to fantastic

405
00:19:19,525 --> 00:19:21,827
possibilities of space travel.

406
00:19:21,827 --> 00:19:25,531
Now, this work needs to start
with fundamental biological

407
00:19:25,531 --> 00:19:26,331
discoveries.

408
00:19:26,331 --> 00:19:28,700
But in order to develop
this as a technology,

409
00:19:28,700 --> 00:19:33,138
we also need to collaborate with
engineers, chemists, physicists,

410
00:19:33,138 --> 00:19:33,906
physicians.

411
00:19:33,906 --> 00:19:36,842
And this is precisely why
there is no place like MIT

412
00:19:36,842 --> 00:19:38,177
to pursue this dream.

413
00:19:38,177 --> 00:19:38,844
Thank you.

414
